  "key_findings": [
    "Canada ranks 5th globally in RAI research output but 44th in AI literacy, indicating a broken pipeline from academic excellence to public understanding.",
    "Canada participates in only 4 of 9 major international RAI governance frameworks identified in Chapter 3, compared to 7+ for leading EU nations.",
    "Global RAI research grew 4x from 2019 to 2024; Canada has maintained its relative position but not gained ground against the US or China.",
    "The EU AI Act and Council of Europe AI Convention represent legally binding frameworks Canada is absent from — a governance gap relative to peer nations.",
    "Fairness and security are the fastest-growing RAI research areas globally in 2024 — Canada's investment through CIFAR/Vector positions it well if governance keeps pace."
  ],
  "strategy_implications": [
    "Canada should leverage its research strength (rank 5) to position itself as a standard-setter, not just a participant, in international RAI governance bodies.",
    "A national AI literacy program is warranted given the gap between research output (5th) and public AI literacy (44th).",
    "Canada should seek observer or signatory status in EU AI Act equivalency frameworks to align its regulatory environment with its largest trading partners.",
    "The CIFAR/Vector/Mila ecosystem should be formally tasked with producing Canada-specific RAI benchmarks and incident tracking infrastructure."
  ]
